"## Abstract\nLight field depth estimation is fundamental for 3D vision, yet estimating depth in non-Lambertian and mixed-material scenes remains highly challenging. Conventional epipolar plane image (EPI) methods rely on a global Lambertian assumption, causing complete failure and texture-copying degradation in specular or scattering regions where angular consistency is violated. To address this, we propose a unified dual-mask physical model integrating signal-processing rigor with physical optics, featuring an MRI-inspired angular frequency analysis mechanism that applies a 2D discrete Fourier transform to 9x9 angular sampling matrices for O(HW) pixel-level reflection classification. Furthermore, we construct a physical framework comprising a medium mask for roughness quantification and an angular direction mask for wavevector deflection, constrained by the radiation tensor field rank, to dynamically schedule component-aware depth estimation branches and fuse them via physically derived weights. Extensive evaluations across five datasets comprising 245 scenes demonstrate that our method reduces the mean absolute error (MAE) in non-Lambertian regions by 49.4% (from 0.411 to 0.208) compared to the EPI baseline, while achieving an overall MAE of 0.125. By unifying the imaging model at the physical optics level, this work provides a theoretically grounded and highly interpretable methodology for robust light field image processing in complex environments.\n\n**Keywords:** Light field depth estimation, Non-Lambertian reflectance, Dual-mask physical model, Angular frequency analysis, Epipolar plane image, Inverse wavevector parsing"